Diagnosis.

Bothriomiris dissimulans

is recognized by the following set of characters: body larger than 6.00 mm; dorsum dark brown with large, yellow and reddish stripes and patches (

Figs. 
1–2

); antennal segment I as long or nearly as long as width of vertex (

Figs. 
1–2

); anterior lobe of pronotum inpunctate (

Fig. 
22

), yellowish, sometimes tinged with red laterally; posterior lobe usually with distinct, yellowish, longitudinal stripe medially (

Figs. 
1–2

); scutellum mostly reddish brown with yellowish, longitudinal stripe medially, originating from base and terminating apically (

Figs. 
1–2

); corium with characteristic Y-shaped, more or less developed, yellow pattern apically (

Figs. 
1–2

); pretarsal claw toothed subapically (

Fig. 
34

); endosoma membranous with DSS thin, relatively short, nearly parallel-sided with ductus seminis; AES relatively long, thin, somewhat embracing DSS; MES fine, sharpened toward apex (

Fig. 
36

); left paramere somewhat rounded, with a sensory lobe only moderately convex (

Fig. 
37

); right paramere with apical half narrowing towards apex, basal process broad, triangular (

Fig. 
38

).

Male genitalia . Endosoma (
Fig. 36
). Membranous with DSS thin, relatively short; AES relatively long, thin, somewhat embracing DSS; MES thin, sharpened toward apex. Left paramere (
Fig. 37
). Somewhat rounded; sensory lobe weakly convex; apical process obtuse. Right paramere (
Fig. 38
). Apical half narrowed toward apex, basal process broad and nearly triangular.

Distribution (
Fig. 19
). China (Hainan), Indonesia (Java, Sulawesi), Malaysia (Pahang, Perak, Borneo, Singapore ), Myanmar , Thailand .

Remarks. Longitudinal pale swelling on posterior lobe of pronotum is lacking in the specimens from Java (see Gorczyca 2006 ,
Fig. 1
).

